			<!-- Begin News/Information Section -->
				<table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" ID="Table23">
					<tr id="trmasthead">
						<td valign="middle" class="main_font" align="center">
							<font size="3"><b>&nbsp;</b></font>
					    </td>
					</tr>
					
					   <td>

			
			
			



<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
<tr>
	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">
  
		<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
		<tr>
		    <td valign="top">
		     <p><font face="Verdana" size="3"><b>Article Title:</b>&nbsp;</font>
		     <font face="Verdana" size="2">Gordon on Hybrids and the EXP penalty</font><br>
		     <a href = "../Subscribe.asp?DID=260657" ><font face="Verdana" size="2">[Subscribe to this document]</font></a></p>
			 </td>
		</tr>
		
		<tr><td>&nbsp;</tr><tr>
		
		    <td valign="top"><div style= "padding:4;float: right"> <script language=JavaScript src=http://www.obsidian-tech.com/absolutebm/abmx.aspx?z=26></script></div><p><font face="Verdana" size="2">
		    <Blockquote>
<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/028157.html">How to eliminate/reduce the hybrid penalty w/o giving free levels--USE MATH</a></B><P>

VI won't reduce the hybrid experience penalty because it will result in existing hybrids getting free levels. This is wrong. They can fix it with some simple algebra. Let's say Hybrid is at 1,000,000 exp points and this levels him to level X.<P>

<B>Yes, it is possible to use math to see that levels don't move around. It's *possible* to do virtually anything given sufficient resources. That said, as mentioned in the FAQ, the experience system is not subject to post-production changes. The experinece system as it exists is part of the game that we will not modify.<P>

It's not appropriate for me to continue trying to make arguments to justify the differing experience requirements, as that suggests that something could happen that would cause us to change our minds. The experience system, as it exists, is absolutely firm: As firm as the game's name being "EverQuest", or it being a game that encourages grouping.<P>

I've tried to address this issue in the past through a number of different methods, but what it comes down to is that it absolutly will not be changed. I am indeed sorry if you disagree.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

I have no problem earning 40% more experience if I'm /actually/ 40% better <P>

<B>Of course that's not how it works :) The experince system isn't set up like it is to as an indication of overall power. Look at rogues and warriors, they have the least experince requirement of anyone yet are rather powerful. It's more a way to control the number of people in the world. <P>

Who would want to play a warrior if a paladin could do everything that they could plus some? They wouldn't. Now, how many people would opt for Paladins were their experience requirement the same as warriors? I imagine that we would have lost a lot of warriors to the hybrids if that were the case, as they are more versatile.</B><P>

They have learned from Verant's mistakes even if Verant hasn't. <P>

<B>Different games, different rules. We very well may make different decisions with future games as well. The point here is that EQ has been released, and this facet of it is not subject to *change*. New development is another matter entirely.<P>

Every game of this type will have things that they do not leave open for changes following release.</B><P>

Is surplus xp earned as you gain a level forfiet? If so then why can you lose your level once you have attained it?<P>

<B>I'm afraid that I don't understand. Experience curves are determined by a combination of race and class. They are not set equal before hand and modified at the time the experience is earned. <P>

In other words, if a hybrid and a warrior just entered 20th level, the hybrid has more experince.<P>

-Gordon</B>
</blockquote>
		    </font></p>
			 </td>
		</tr>
